<div class="d-r">
  <div class="s">When to Stop</div>
  <p>Severe injection site reactions (spreading redness, swelling, signs of infection), allergic reactions (difficulty breathing, facial swelling, widespread hives), or persistent worsening of symptoms. Consult your provider immediately.</p>
</div>

<p>For a broader overview, see our <a href="/articles/peptide-side-effects-what-to-know">peptide side effects guide</a>.</p>

<!-- ========== COMPARISON ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>SS-31 vs. MOTS-c: Two Approaches to Mitochondrial Health</h2>

<p>Both SS-31 and <a href="/articles/mots-c-mitochondrial-peptide">MOTS-c</a> are called "mitochondrial peptides," but they work through completely different mechanisms.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>SS-31 (Elamipretide)</th><th>MOTS-c</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Origin</strong></td><td>Synthetic (lab-designed)</td><td>Endogenous (mitochondrial DNA)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Target</strong></td><td>Cardiolipin on inner membrane</td><td>AMPK pathway, nuclear gene regulation</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td><td>Stabilizes electron transport chain</td><td>Activates cellular energy sensor</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Primary effects</strong></td><td>Restores structure &#38; ATP production</td><td>Metabolic regulation, insulin sensitivity</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Clinical trials</strong></td><td class="g">Multiple phase 2/3, one FDA approval</td><td class="y">Very early development</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>FDA status</strong></td><td class="g">Approved (Barth syndrome)</td><td class="r">Not approved</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Best studied for</strong></td><td>Heart failure, genetic mitochondrial disease</td><td>Metabolic syndrome, obesity, exercise</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Half-life</strong></td><td>~3&ndash;4 hours</td><td>Not well characterized in humans</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="d-p">
  <div class="s">Bottom Line</div>
  <p>SS-31 works from the inside out, physically stabilizing the machinery that makes ATP. MOTS-c works from the outside in, activating signaling pathways that tell cells to ramp up energy metabolism. They're complementary rather than competing approaches.</p>
</div>

<p>For structural mitochondrial damage (aging, genetic disease, ischemia), SS-31 has stronger evidence. For metabolic dysfunction and insulin resistance, MOTS-c may be more relevant.</p>

<!-- ========== WHO BENEFITS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Who Might Benefit</h2>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="cd ct">
    <div class="tg">Strong Evidence</div>
    <h3>Barth Syndrome Patients</h3>
    <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;">The only FDA-approved indication. Demonstrated clinical benefit in a controlled trial.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="cd cb">
    <div class="tg">Moderate Evidence</div>
    <h3>Mitochondrial Myopathies</h3>
